fix(Interaction): reactivate collisions when an object is ungrabbed

The ability to pause collisions on the object when it is grabbed would
cause an issue if the object was dropped (ungrabbed) whilst the
pause collisions was still active where the object could fall through
the wall as collisions were still disabled on it.

The fix is to unpause the collisions as soon as the object is dropped.

Merge pull request #711 from thestonefox/feat/second_grab_actions

Feat/second grab actions - resolves #31 - resolves #225

chore(README): fix waffle badge image link

For some reason GitHub is no longer accepting a `?` in the
link url even though the url is still valid via a browser. The quick
solution is to just remove the optional parameters from the
waffle badge url.

feat(Interaction): add secondary grab action to control direction

A new Secondary Controller Grab Action has been added to control
the direction of the grabbed interactable object by grabbing with
the second controller.

The example scene for Secondary Controller Actions has been updated
to display this new function.

feat(Interaction): add custom secondary grab action to scale objects

A new Custom Secondary Action has been added to the Interactable Object
that takes a new `SecondaryControllerGrabActions` script that defines
the behaviour of what should happen when a second controller grabs
an already grabbed object.

The first Secondary Controller Grab Action to be added is a basic
scale object that will cause the object to scale in the direction the
controller is being moved and it also has parameters on the custom
script to lock certain axis from being scaled.

A new example scene has been added that demonstrates scaling objects.

chore(README): update one of the last link to steam store page

One Of The Last now has a steam store page, so it's better to
the store page for driving customers.

fix(Interaction): ensure track object snap handle uses same orientation

The snap handles on a Track Object grab mechanic would always be
inverted due to the way the code inverted the rotation to ensure the
snap handle could be rotated towards.

This fix simply flips the snap handle rotations on object Awake so
they are already inverted before they get inverted again in the
fixed update.

feat(Interaction): add ability to utilise secondary controller grab

  > **Breaking Changes**

The `Is Swappable` parameter has now been removed from the interactable
object and is replaced with a new `Secondary Controller Grab Action`
that at the moment performs the same concept of either:

 * No action: When the second controller grabs the item doesn't swap.
 * Swap controller: When the second controller grabs the item swaps
 to the new controller hand.

The Interactable Object now also tracks the grab of both controllers,
the first controller to grab is considered holding the object and
the second controller to grab is considered to be influencing the
object or to have a specific action.

fix(RoomExtender): ensure gizmo adheres to coding standards

The RoomExtender gizmo was missing an accessibility keyword from one
of the private methods.

fix(ConsoleViewerCanvas): add VRTK_UICanvas to make prefab work

Since the VRTK_UICanvas has been introduced, all interactable
canvases require this script applied to them. The Console Viewer Canvas
also requires this script to be applied.

Merge pull request #694 from thestonefox/fix/interaction-issues

fix(Interaction): ensure using state is set correctly after touch/grab - resolves #688

fix(Interaction): ensure using state is set correctly after touch/grab

The Using state of an Interactable Object would get out of sync due to
the previous method of stopping an object's use method utilising a
co-routine at the end of the frame.

This was implemented due to StopTouching always being called even when
an object is grabbed. The fix is to remove the Coroutine as it causes
too many issues and to fix the issue at StopTouching by preventing
a stop touch event in the LateUpdate if the object is actually being
grabbed by the touching object, if it's being grabbed then it hasn't
stopped being touched in that instance.

This means that the Using action can get override correctly and no
artifacts are introduced at the end of the frame when stop using was
being called again, creating corruption with the Using State.

The toggle controller visibility has also been fixed by ensuring the
current controller visibility is stored and restored on grab and on
use events.

The `UsingAGrabbedObject` example scene has been updated to provide
more variations of grab and use to aid test interactions.

The slack badge in the readme was using the redirect url to
point to the image, yet this never seemed to update the GitHub

feat(UIPointer): add events for click, drag start and drag end

There are 3 new events for the UI Pointer to emit now:

 * `Click` when the pointer has clicked on an element
 * `DragStart` when the pointer starts dragging a valid element
 * `DragEnd` when the pointer stops dragging a valid element

There has also been a fix of how the UIPointer registers it's id in
the event data as this is now done in a coroutine which waits for
the controller tracked object id to be set before setting the
UIPointer event data id.

feat(UICanvas): add ability to drag and drop UI elements on canvas

Two scripts have been added to provide a customised drag and drop
function for UI elements.

The `VRTK_UIDraggableItem` script is applied to any UI Element inside
a `VRTK_UICanvas` object and will allow for the UI Element to be
dragged around the canvas and dropped onto the canvas in a new
location.

The `VRTK_UIDropZone` script provides a restriction for where the
draggable items can be dropped. If the draggable item is restricted
to a UI Drop Zone then it can only be dropped if it is being hovered
over a drop zone otherwise when it is dropped, it will snap back
to it's original position.

The UI Example scene has been updated with a new canvas to show the
drag and drop ability.

feat(UICanvas): add ui canvas script for defining valid canvas targets

  > **Breaking Changes**

Previously, the UI Pointer was responsible for configuring any
World Space canvases to be compatible with the UI Pointer. However,
this was limiting for a number of reasons:

 * Newly created canvases had to be registered with the UI Pointer
 * Turning off a canvas for interaction was through the UI Pointer
 * Any canvas specific options had to be uniform over all canvases
 * It acted too much like magic having the pointer know how to set
 the canvases up.

The new solution now requires any World Space canvas to have a
UI Canvas script added to it and this will set up the canvas to be
interactable by a UI Pointer. Removing or disabling the UI Canvas
script will reset the canvas back to it's original state and it will
no longer be interactable by the UI Poiinter.

The example scene has been updated to reflect the change and show
how canvases can have independent options now.

feat(Pointer): allow custom transform origin on pointers

The WorldPointer and UIPointer can now both accept a custom transform
to be used as the origin of the pointer (and raycast). This is useful
if the starting position of the pointer and the forward direction
of the pointer is required to be changed. For instance, it's now
possible to rotate the pointers to come out of the controller (or
attached object) at a different angle or from a different position
rather than the centre of the object.

feat(UIPointer): automatically activate UI ray within given distance

A new option has been added to the UI Pointer that will automatically
activate the UI raycast when the game object containing a UI Pointer
gets within a given distance of a valid canvas.

The PlayerObject script has been updated as well to be able to
identify player objects that are considered colliders.

feat(UIPointer): add click ui elements with pointer collision

A new setting has been added that will activate the click action on
the UI Pointer if the object the UIPointer is attached to collides
with a valid UI canvas. This allows a UI element to be clicked simply
by activating the UI raycast and touching the UI element.

This works by the ray is active and pointing at a UI element then the
collision forces a click and the UI element that is being touched by
the raycast is considered clicked.
